While reiterating North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took step-by-step action, its statement was important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made in Singapore on 12 June at the first summit between an American President and a North Korean leader, when Kim committed to working for a "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee the security of North Korea.
North Korea is seeking to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang should first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refused requests to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
the United States insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and increases pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, even in opposition to the "declaration of the end of war".
"Those who think that these sanctions can cause us to rain don't know us.
