National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in the area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these single flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The study of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-earned brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of different species.
A map and a report on habitat will be prepared to develop a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as prairie creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perch and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as tollpapers and certain chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as company cat attacks.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles to their flight route.
In charge of the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch and sometimes rescue inspections.
The organization has also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats on the site of Thrave in Dumfries-et-Gallow, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
David Thompson, domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Thrave, we have an ideal place for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so that the work we do here and in other places will help us to better understand what the bats need to thrive."
It stresses the importance of verifying the presence of bats before maintaining the properties, because by destroying it without wanting a single maternity nest, the death of 400 females and small females can be caused, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, to disturb them, or to destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have much to learn about our bats and about many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations for now."
